<subSubSection box="[216,1411,1283,1311]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[182,1545,1281,2435]" box="[216,1411,1283,1311]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[216,406,1283,1311]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Etymology</emphasis>
. — Named after the disc-like structure at the base of the superior appendages.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="426" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[182,1545,1281,2435]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[216,485,1329,1363]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Description</emphasis>
. — Small-sized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[773,953,1329,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[773,953,1329,1363]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with pale disc-like structures located at base of male superior appendages.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[182,1545,1281,2435]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
MALE. — Labium pale whitish yellow. Labrum shiny metallic green with lateral distal borders pale yellow. Base of mandibles pale yellow. Anteclypeus blackish spotted with pale yellow. Postclypeus, firms, top of head and rear of head shiny metallic green. Antennae black with small pale yellow spot at base. Ocelli pale yellow. The frontal head is illustrated 
<emphasis box="[348,379,1624,1658]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">in</emphasis>
<figureCitation box="[388,523,1624,1658]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="1.[182,237,1613,1641]" captionTargetBox="[182,1012,380,1555]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1-8. [1-3] Rhinocypha chaoi sp. n., ♂: (1) hindwing; (2) tho­ rax, lateral; (3) abdomen, lateral; [4-8] Megalestes discus sp. n„ ♂J: (4) head, frontal: (5) thorax, lateral; (6) penile organ, ventral; (7) caudal appendages, dorsal; (8) caudal appendages, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3375620/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Figure 4</figureCitation>
. Prothorax blackish metallic green with pale yellow frontal lobe, rear lobes and lateral margin. Dorsum of synthorax and mesepimeron shiny, dark metallic green with black humeral suture (
<figureCitation box="[760,856,1723,1757]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="1.[182,237,1613,1641]" captionTargetBox="[182,1012,380,1555]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1-8. [1-3] Rhinocypha chaoi sp. n., ♂: (1) hindwing; (2) tho­ rax, lateral; (3) abdomen, lateral; [4-8] Megalestes discus sp. n„ ♂J: (4) head, frontal: (5) thorax, lateral; (6) penile organ, ventral; (7) caudal appendages, dorsal; (8) caudal appendages, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3375620/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[760,817,1723,1757]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Fig</emphasis>
. 5
</figureCitation>
). Metepisternum shiny, dark metallic green with pale yellow stripe which 
<emphasis box="[670,696,1772,1806]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">is</emphasis>
broad anteriorly and narrows towards posterior. The pale yellow stripe 
<emphasis box="[472,498,1821,1855]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">is</emphasis>
finely bordered with black margin. Metepimeron and metaposternum pale yellow. Coxae pale yellow. Legs pale brown outer faces and dark brown 
<emphasis box="[1455,1537,1871,1905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">inner</emphasis>
, ventral faces. Wings hyaline with dark brown pterostigma, covering three cells, braced at anterior margin. First two segments blackish above with metallic green reflection and pale yellow below. Segments 3-5 bronzy brown with faint metallic green reflection. Segments 6-8 dark brown with metallic green reflection. Segments 9-10 blackish brown with faint metallic green reflection covered in whitish 
<emphasis box="[1051,1258,2117,2151]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">pruinescence</emphasis>
prior to preservation. Superior appendages blackish with pale disk-like structure at dorsal base (
<figureCitation box="[1394,1524,2167,2201]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="1.[182,237,1613,1641]" captionTargetBox="[182,1012,380,1555]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1-8. [1-3] Rhinocypha chaoi sp. n., ♂: (1) hindwing; (2) tho­ rax, lateral; (3) abdomen, lateral; [4-8] Megalestes discus sp. n„ ♂J: (4) head, frontal: (5) thorax, lateral; (6) penile organ, ventral; (7) caudal appendages, dorsal; (8) caudal appendages, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3375620/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[1394,1464,2167,2201]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Figs</emphasis>
7-8
</figureCitation>
). Quadrate, peg-like projection, bifurcated at tip, downward and posterior pointing, originating from inside face of the superior appendage below disk-like structure. Inferior appendages with stout central posterior directed projection beset at tip with long upwardly curved orange brown hairs. Penile organ 
<emphasis box="[835,861,2362,2396]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">is</emphasis>
illustrated in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="1.[182,237,1613,1641]" captionTargetBox="[182,1012,380,1555]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1-8. [1-3] Rhinocypha chaoi sp. n., ♂: (1) hindwing; (2) tho­ rax, lateral; (3) abdomen, lateral; [4-8] Megalestes discus sp. n„ ♂J: (4) head, frontal: (5) thorax, lateral; (6) penile organ, ventral; (7) caudal appendages, dorsal; (8) caudal appendages, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3375620/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
Figure 6. 
<paragraph blockId="3.[182,1545,1281,2435]" box="[217,1092,2407,2435]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Measurements (mm). - abd. + app.49.0-50.0,hw 32.0-35.0.</paragraph>
</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="427" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[185,1540,382,866]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis box="[220,446,390,418]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">differential</emphasis>
DIAGNOSIS. — There are five 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[920,1098,386,420]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[920,1098,386,420]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from China. These comprise 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chao" authorityYear="1947" box="[446,800,436,470]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chengi">
<emphasis box="[446,605,436,470]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. chengi</emphasis>
Chao, 1947
</taxonomicName>
from Fujian, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham" authorityYear="1930" box="[1021,1452,436,470]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distans">
<emphasis box="[1021,1187,436,470]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. distans</emphasis>
Needham, 1930
</taxonomicName>
from Guangxi, Jiangxi and Sichuan 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham" authorityYear="1930" box="[683,1100,485,519]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heros">
<emphasis box="[683,828,485,519]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. heros</emphasis>
Needham, 1930
</taxonomicName>
from Fujian, Zhejiang and possibly Sichuan, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1947" box="[471,793,535,569]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maai">
<emphasis box="[471,603,535,569]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. maai</emphasis>
Chen, 1947
</taxonomicName>
from Taiwan, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham" authorityYear="1930" box="[1028,1453,535,569]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micans">
<emphasis box="[1028,1192,535,569]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. micans</emphasis>
Needham, 1930
</taxonomicName>
from Sichuan, Yunnan and Assam and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1935" box="[726,1067,584,618]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riccii">
<emphasis box="[726,861,584,618]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. riccii</emphasis>
Navas, 1935
</taxonomicName>
from Jiangxi. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilson" authorityYear="2004" box="[1296,1447,584,618]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discus">
<emphasis box="[1296,1447,584,618]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. discus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only Chinese member of the genus to possess superior appendages with basal disc-like structures. It 
<emphasis box="[392,417,683,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">is</emphasis>
closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lahiri" authorityYear="1979" box="[705,897,683,717]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lieftincki">
<emphasis box="[705,897,683,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">M. lieftincki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="LAHIRI, A. R." box="[907,1160,683,717]" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" pagination="119 - 132" part="13" refId="ref5301" refString="LAHIRI, A. R., 1979. Odonata (Insecta) from different States of North Eastern India. Oriental Insects 13 (1 / 2): 119 - 132." title="Odonata (Insecta) from different States of North Eastern India" type="journal article" year="1979">LAHIRI (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, which 
<emphasis box="[1284,1310,683,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">is</emphasis>
the only other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[185,363,733,767]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[185,363,733,767]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to possess 
<emphasis box="[668,798,733,767]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">superior</emphasis>
appendages with distinctive basal expansions. The inferior appendages of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lahiri" authorityYear="1979" box="[623,759,782,816]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lieftincki">
<emphasis box="[623,759,782,816]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">lieftincki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have an upward pointing spine (absent in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilson" authorityYear="2004" box="[1428,1527,782,816]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discus">discus</taxonomicName>
) in
</emphasis>
addition to the curved tip.
</paragraph>
